	Argument parser for C & C++ programming languages.

Features:
	* shortname flags
	./p -v
	./p -h

	* arguments for shortname flags
	./p -n 4
	./p -v[*] Where * is any kind of argument

	* longname flags
	./p --help
	./p --verbose

	* arguments for longname flags
	./p --cmd <command>
	./p --cmd=<command>

	* combinability
	./p -abc

	will be read as

	./p -a -b -c

	if any argument is given to that sequence, then that argument will be associated
	to the last flag present (-c in this case)

	* positional arguments
	./p [flags] -- posarg1 posarg2 ... posargN

	if any positional argument is given before '--', it will be taken as an argument to
	to the last flag seen

Flags:
	A flag is anything that starts with a dash in the arguments provided via terminal, to define
	a flag that the program is supposed to know about the programmer has the following structure

	struct GetoFlag {
		union {
			char *asText;
			double asDouble;
			unsigned long asUnsignedLong;
			unsigned int asUnisignedInt;
			signed long asSignedLong;
			signed int asSignedInt;
		} argument;
		const char *longname;
		const char *description;
		const char shortname;
		const getopts_t opts;
	};

	- longname: flag's fullname
	- shortname: flag's alias
	- description: flag's purpose in case usage is displayed
	- opts: opts is defined as an unsigned char which contains the following
	        information:

			* indicates whether the flag takes an argument or not:
				- GETO_ARG_IS_NONEXISTENT      (0b00000001)
				- GETO_ARG_IS_OPTIONAL         (0b00000010)
				- GETO_ARG_IS_MANDATORY        (0b00000011)

			* indicates the type of argument the flag should expect
				- GETO_ARG_TYPE_TEXT           (0b00000100)
				- GETO_ARG_TYPE_DOUB           (0b00001100)
				- GETO_ARG_TYPE_UI64           (0b00001000)
				- GETO_ARG_TYPE_UI32           (0b00010000)
				- GETO_ARG_TYPE_SI64           (0b00010100)
				- GETO_ARG_TYPE_SI32           (0b00011100)

